HEADWORD: Hobbletehoy
<hw>Hob"ble*te*hoy`</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>hobbetyhoy</asp>, <asp>hobbarddehoy</asp>, <asp>hobbedehoy</asp>,
<asp>hobdehoy</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[ Cf. Prob. E. <ets>hobbledygee</ets>
with a limping movement; also F. <ets>hobereau</ets>, a country squire,
E. <ets>hobby</ets>, and OF. <ets>hoi</ets> to-day; perh. the orig.
sense was, an upstart of to-day.]</ety> <def>A youth between boy and
man; an awkward, gawky young fellow .</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the men, boys, and <qex>hobbledehoys</qex> attached to the
farm.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens. .</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hobbler</ent>⟦br⟧
